  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Backstory is the history that precedes the narrative\u0026rsquo;s present — what happened before the story begins. A character\u0026rsquo;s childhood, a war that shaped the world, a relationship that ended before page one — all are backstory. The writer needs to know it; the reader needs only as much of it as the present story requires.\nThe challenge of backstory is delivery. The writer who has invented a rich history is tempted to share it all, but backstory that arrives before the reader cares about the present situation is dead weight. The most effective approach is to reveal backstory in fragments, when the present action makes it relevant — a detail of childhood surfacing during a crisis, a past betrayal mentioned when trust is at stake.\n",
